 {"id":"br-aa0nj","title":"Attention Feed Phase 0: Ratify the contract, guardrails, and JSON semantics","description":"# Why this bead exists
ntm already has `--robot-snapshot`, `--robot-wait`, `--robot-logs`, `--robot-dashboard`, and other machine interfaces, but the semantics are spread across commands and implementation details. Before code changes begin, the project needs one explicit contract for the new attention-feed surfaces so later implementation does not drift.

# Goals
- Make the intended operator loop obvious: `snapshot -> events/digest/attention -> targeted follow-up`.
- Preserve current robot JSON conventions for `success`, `timestamp`, empty arrays, omitted optional fields, and error codes.
- Keep the design subordinate to the existing flywheel method: LLM drives, ntm senses and actuates.

# Scope
1. Define the normalized event envelope fields and their meaning: `cursor`, `ts`, `session`, `pane`, `category`, `type`, `source`, `actionability`, `severity`, `summary`, `details`, `next_actions`.
2. Define cursor semantics: monotonicity, replay rules, retention, expiration, and the exact `CURSOR_EXPIRED` / resync contract.
3. Define the minimal command cluster: `--robot-snapshot`, `--robot-events`, `--robot-digest`, `--robot-wait`, `--robot-attention`.
4. Define named wait conditions and explicitly reject a free-form condition DSL.
5. Define actionability classes (`background`, `interesting`, `action_required`) and how they differ from severity.
6. Define rules for `next_actions`: they must be mechanical follow-ups only, and they must point to real robot surfaces rather than hypothetical future commands.
7. Define parity requirements so CLI, HTTP, SSE, and WebSocket clients are not forced to learn different schemas.
8. Define how help/capabilities output will teach the cold-start loop and the expired-cursor resync path.
9. Define the contract-level semantics for profiles/defaults: whether a default profile exists, how an explicitly requested profile is represented, and how profile presets interact with explicit filters.
10. Define how unsupported or degraded conditions must be surfaced across snapshot/help/capabilities/dashboard/terse outputs so later beads cannot quietly hide partial observability.
11. Define any contract-visible fields or markers needed for summary surfaces to represent degraded state honestly without inventing a forked schema later.
12. Define machine-readable schema/capability version markers and transport-liveness semantics, including any heartbeat/keepalive expectations that long-lived clients need in order to distinguish quiet from dead connections.

# Deliverables for future implementers
This bead should leave behind enough specificity that later work can be implemented without consulting any external markdown plan. That means concrete example payloads, explicit field semantics, and explicit error examples should exist in the bead body and later be mirrored in code/tests/help output.

# Guardrails / non-goals
- No planner, scheduler, or mission runtime.
- No second source of truth for task state or coordination state.
- No opaque magic heuristics that cannot be explained in code comments or tests.
- No reliance on external markdown after this bead graph is created; the intent must be captured in the code, help, tests, and bead descriptions.

# Detailed verification expectations
- Golden fixtures for at least: successful snapshot bootstrap, successful event replay, successful digest, successful attention wake, and `CURSOR_EXPIRED`.
- Golden fixtures or schema examples for: default-profile behavior, explicit profile behavior, contradictory profile/filter behavior, degraded/unsupported summary markers, schema-version markers, and transport-liveness markers.
- Help/capabilities examples that show the canonical operator loop, the exact condition names, the profile/default semantics, and any heartbeat/reconnect expectations relevant to long-lived clients.
- Logging notes that tell future implementers where contract mismatches should be surfaced when commands cannot satisfy replay/resume guarantees.

# Acceptance criteria
- [ ] The contract is explicit enough that later beads can implement against it without consulting any outside plan.
- [ ] Example success and error payloads are concrete enough to become tests and help output.
- [ ] The boundary "LLM is the driver; ntm is the nervous system" is stated unambiguously.
- [ ] The design preserves the existing robot-mode exit-code and JSON-semantics conventions.
- [ ] Snapshot bootstrap semantics are specified as explicitly as feed/digest semantics.
- [ ] Profile/default semantics, degraded-summary semantics, and transport-liveness/schema-version semantics are specified at the contract layer rather than being left implicit.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":120,"created_at":"2026-03-21T00:49:19.221285885Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T02:37:34.885137590Z","closed_at":"2026-03-21T02:37:34.884434295Z","close_reason":"Contract implemented in attention_contract.go with event envelope, cursor semantics, command cluster, actionability classes, profiles, and golden fixtures","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention-feed","contract","phase-0","robot"]}
 {"id":"br-abp0s","title":"Overlay-Feed T3: Upgrade zoom hint to include feed cursor for agent continuity","description":"# Upgrade Zoom Hint to Include Feed Cursor and Emit Human Events

## Background

When a user zooms into a pane from the overlay (z/Enter), the popup closes and a tmux display-message hint appears:
    F12 -> dashboard overlay · prefix+z -> unzoom

This hint is human-facing. But in the integrated world, a tending agent might be watching the session too. When the human zooms, the agent should know: which pane was zoomed, the current feed cursor (so the agent can resume from that point), and that the human is actively interacting.

## What To Build

### 1. Include cursor in the display-message (if feed available)
- Current: "F12 -> dashboard overlay · prefix+z -> unzoom"
- New: "F12 -> dashboard overlay · prefix+z -> unzoom · cursor:42135"
- The cursor value comes from the Attention Feed journal current position
- If the feed is not available, omit the cursor portion (graceful degradation)

### 2. Emit "human.zoom" event to the Attention Feed
- When a user zooms from the overlay, publish a BusEvent with type "human.zoom"
- Include: session, pane_index, agent_type, timestamp
- Actionability: "background" (informational, not attention-worthy)
- This lets a tending agent know the human is looking at a specific pane

### 3. Emit "human.overlay_dismiss" event when Escape is pressed
- When the user presses Escape to close the overlay, publish "human.overlay_dismiss"
- Include: session, timestamp, duration_seconds (how long overlay was open)
- Actionability: "background"
- Requires tracking when the overlay was opened (add overlayOpenedAt field to Model)

### 4. Define new event type constants
- Add HumanZoom and HumanOverlayDismiss to the event type constants
- Follow the naming convention of existing event types (e.g., EventAgentIdle in internal/notify/notify.go)

## Unit Test Requirements

- Test display-message includes cursor when journal is available (mock journal)
- Test display-message omits cursor when journal is not available
- Test human.zoom event is published with correct fields
- Test human.overlay_dismiss event includes duration
- Test overlayOpenedAt is set when popup mode activates
- Test event actionability is always "background" for human events

## Technical Notes

- The cursor value comes from the event journal (once br-xmmaj is built)
- Use events.DefaultBus.Publish() for event publishing
- The overlayOpenedAt field should be set in the Init() method when popupMode=true
- Duration is calculated as time.Since(m.overlayOpenedAt) when Escape is pressed

## Dependencies

- Depends on: Attention Feed Phase 1a (br-xmmaj) — cursor model for cursor in hint
- Depends on: Attention Feed Phase 1b (br-7v4ns) — event mapping should include human-originated events

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Display-message includes cursor when feed available
- [ ] Display-message works without cursor when feed unavailable
- [ ] human.zoom event published on zoom from overlay
- [ ] human.overlay_dismiss event published on Escape
- [ ] Events follow normalized envelope format
- [ ] overlayOpenedAt tracked for duration calculation
- [ ] Unit tests for all scenarios
- [ ] go build and go vet pass","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:05:03.228742439Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T08:10:28.790407619Z","closed_at":"2026-03-21T08:10:28.789391108Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention-feed","dashboard","overlay","phase-2","robot"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-abp0s","depends_on_id":"br-7v4ns","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:11:31.409733650Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-abp0s","depends_on_id":"br-x66gc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:37.095275066Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-abp0s","depends_on_id":"br-xmmaj","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:27.410698650Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
